Please note that the SEISC Board of Controls have decided to make things easier with gate money & it will now cost $5.00/person to attend baseball and softball games, this does also include students & senior citizens. This is SEISC Conference wide so these will be the prices at every SEISC BB/SB event.

All Highland event & staff passes that have been purchased for the 2019-2020 as well as lifetime passes, etc. from the school year will be honored.

Also please remember that there will be no concessions this season as well and you will be allowed to bring in your own drinks and snacks. If you are bringing coolers into the property those will be inspected as well.

Please cleanup after yourselves at the end of the evening as well.

Also we are attaching the guidelines from the Athletic Associations as well.

Thank you!!!

Please note that the SEISC Board of Controls have decided to make things easier with gate money & it will now cost $5.00/person to attend baseball and softball games, this does also include students & senior citizens. This is SEISC Conference wide so these will be the prices at every SEISC BB/SB event.

All Highland event & staff passes that have been purchased for the 2019-2020 as well as lifetime passes, etc. from the school year will be honored.

Also please remember that there will be no concessions this season as well and you will be allowed to bring in your own drinks and snacks. If you are bringing coolers into the property those will be inspected as well.

Please cleanup after yourselves at the end of the evening as well.

Also we are attaching the guidelines from the Athletic Associations as well.

Thank you!!!
Highland Huskies Athletic Department.

https://ighsau.org/upl/downloads/library/posters-2020-allposters.pdf

post_text:
June 2, 2020

Highland Students and Community,

I regret to inform you that after much careful consideration, we have decided to cancel our Prom activities. This decision was not made lightly. We have sought advice from other school administrators and public health officials. After discussing our options with others and referring to CDC recommendations we have decided that having Prom could not be done in a way that would adequately protect the health of our students. While I apologize for the inconvenience of delaying this announcement, I chose to wait in the hope that regulations might be lifted and students would be able to enjoy a traditional Prom. I empathize with your disappointment in having another significant event cancelled. The health and safety of our students is foremost in our thoughts and concerns.

Sincerely,

Angela Hazelett

Highland High School Principal

Highland High School Presents

Zach Willman

Class of 2020

Plans after graduation:
I plan to attend Kirkwood Community College and take the Diagnostic Assistant Program. Then transfer to Mercy and St. Luke’s School of Radiologic Technology to pursue a career in Radiology.

Activities:
I have been a part of the Highland Shooting Sports team - trap shooting. I have also been a member of NHS (National Honor Society) at Highland.

Favorite Memory:
My favorite memory was my junior year, as it was a full year of school and memories.

Most Influential Staff Member:
Mr. Ball has been the most influential staff member I have worked with at Highland. He has helped me make the right educational decisions/choices on what classes to take that would benefit me the most. I am now one big step ahead on college classes, as well as being more prepared for college thanks to Mr. Ball. So, thank you Mr. Ball!

What will you miss most about high school?
I will miss being around friends and going to sporting events.

Guidance from Governor Kim Reynolds:

SUMMER SCHOOL ACTIVITIES

SECTION THREE. Pursuant to Iowa Code § 135.144(13), and in conjunction with the Iowa Department of Public Health and the Iowa Department of Education, unless otherwise modified by subsequent proclamation, a public school or nonpublic school, as defined in Iowa Code § 280.2, may reopen for school-sponsored activities and learning effective June 1, 2020, but only to the extent that such activities and learning are consistent with guidance of the Iowa Department of Education, the Iowa High School Athletic Association, and the Iowa Girls High School Athletic Union, as applicable. Any such school-sponsored activity that is conducted consistent with this guidance shall not be a violation of the prohibition on social, community, recreational, leisure, and sporting gatherings and events of more than 10 people under section 5 of the Proclamation of Disaster Emergency issued on May 13, 2020.

Highland High School Presents

Shalyn Kirk

Class of 2020

Plans after graduation:
I plan to attend Mount Mercy University and study Nursing.

Activities:
While at Highland, I have been involved in: Basketball, Track, Volleyball, Softball, Choir, Band, recording the musicals, and NHS

Favorite Memory:
My favorite memory of attending Highland is when we had a Softball game and Zane Arnold was on the roof of the school and he fell through one of the skylights and landed right in front of Mrs. Schaffer. He scrambled for his glasses, got up, and ran. I still wish we would gotten this on video!

Most Influential Staff Member:
The most influential staff member that I have worked with is Mr. Ball. There were often times I would go into his office and not have a clue what I was doing, just in a bad mood, or couldn’t find the confidence to do something. He was always ready to help me in the best way he could.

What will you miss most about high school?
Definitely all of the relationships that I made whether it be with students or faculty.

post_text:
Highland Community School District Receives Donation from Elite Sports Challenge to Start the Highland Coat Closet

During April, Elite Sports put together a “We Got Spirit” challenge to the Highland CSD for staff, students, coaches, and families to submit videos showing their school spirit wearing their favorite Highland gear. Along with the video challenge Elite Sports sold t-shirts with a portion of every shirt purchased coming back to the school. Today, School Counselor Derick Ball and School Nurse Cindy Peiffer accepted a check in the amount of $855.00. That money is going to be used to start the Highland Coat Closet. Thank you to everyone who participated in the video challenge as well as to everyone who purchased t-shirts. Thank you to Mr. Ball and Nurse Cindy for starting the Coat Closer and especially a HUGE THANK YOU to everyone who purchased t-shirts, without all of you this would not have been made possible.

#HuskyPride

Congratulations to our Highland Agriculture Department and Instructor Mrs. Trower:

On Tuesday, April 7, 2020, the Southeast Iowa Regional STEM Advisory Board of the Iowa Governor’s STEM Advisory Council released an e-mail to the Highland Agriculture Department stating that the department would be awarded their STEM Scale-Up Program application for CASE – Agricultural Power and Technology.

The board reviewed many applications from teachers, administrators and informal educators—all excited to bring exemplary STEM programs to Iowa’s students. In the Southeast region alone, the board received 148 requests for programs on the 2020-21 STEM Scale-Up Program menu.

The Iowa FFA Foundation is the program provider for the grant and provides professional development and training on how to successfully implement the new CASE curriculum within the Highland Agriculture Department."

Thank you for supporting our students!
--

#HuskyPride

Highland High School Presents

Emily Yahnke

Class of 2020

Plans after graduation: I plan to attend the University of Iowa to major in Elementary Education.

Activities:
During High School I have been involved in track, softball, wrestling cheer, basketball, cross country, and student council.

Favorite Memory:
Playing sports/attending sporting events with friends and also becoming a state champion in long jump my sophomore year.

Most Influential Staff Member:
The most influential staff member I have worked with at Highland is Mr. Eaton. I had the opportunity to help him out with some of his classes my senior year and it has influenced me to want to become an elementary teacher.

What will you miss most about high school?
Playing sports with my friends.

Highland High School Presents

Alyssa Brase

Class of 2020

Plans after graduation:
After graduation I plan to attend the University of Iowa and study physical therapy specializing in spina bifida.

Activities:
While attending Highland I have been involved in choir, the musical, the tutoring program, volleyball, basketball, and soccer

Favorite Memory:
Favorite memory while attending highland is being able to play soccer with my older brother.

Most Influential Staff Member:
Patrek Tufts. Even though he was not there for my freshman or senior year he was for my sophomore and junior year. In this little time he taught me how to be a bigger person in tough situations. I guess he also taught me math.

What will you miss most about high school?
The thing I will miss most about high school is being able to be a part of a small, loving community.

post_text:
Highland High School Presents

Bill Laughlin

Class of 2020

Plans after graduation:
Attend the University of Kansas and major in Computer Science.

Activities:
I have been involved in Baseball, basketball, track, and the National Honor Society.

Favorite Memory:
My senior basketball season will be something I will remember for the rest of my life. The entire season as a whole is my favorite memory.

Most Influential Staff Member:
Mr. Zywiec easily. I first met him as a staff member when I took Pre-Algebra in 7th grade. He instantly became one of my favorites. As the years went on, I grew more and more fond of him until our senior year, he became the basketball coach. As our head basketball coach, he showed me just how much he cares about each and every-one of us. I can always count on him if I need anything. Mr. Zywiec is not just a staff member, he is our friend, and has created a relationship that will last him forever.

What will you miss most about high school?
The students and faculty.

RFDTV.COM
HOME

Highland FFA
April 7 at 9:00 PM ·

Want watch and hear about Highland FFA on RFD TV this Saturday, check out the information below!

The Highland FFA chapter will be featured on This Week in Agribusiness, which airs on RFDtv for the weekend of Apr 11-12, 2020. They're going to be using a snip it from an interview with Highland FFA President, Bryce Waters, from National Convention, back in October.

Airing info...........TWIA airs on RFDtv four times throughout each weekend. Air times are (all times central) 7:00a.m. on Saturdays, 5:00a.m. and 9:30p.m. on Sundays.

RFDtv is viewed via satellite on either Dish Network Channel 231 or DirecTV Channel 345. You can check the television airing schedule on RFD-TV at www.rfdtv.com

Each tribute as it aired is also posted on our website at www.farmprogress.com/week-agribusiness. Click on the "Highlights" video and find the Nationwide sponsored segment (Part 6). This is updated weekly – so it stays on for one week.

Highland Secondary School

Highland High School Presents

Abigayle Clifton

Class of 2020
Plans after graduation:
After graduation I plan on attending Kirkwood community college for the engineering program.

Activities:
While at highland I participated in choir and golf. I also did the spotlight during the musicals.

Favorite Memory:
My favorite memory of attending highland is attending all the sporting events and cheering on my friends and cousins.

Most Influential Staff Member:
The most influential staff member has been Mrs. Trees. She encouraged me to do well in art class.

What will you miss most about high school?
What I will miss about high school is being around all my friends, attending sporting events, and having fun with the teachers.

Highland Pride right here. A small but mighty group of Highland Staff and their hubbies helped put together 1100 Breakfasts and 1100 Lunches today for the kids that will be handed out this upcoming week. We cannot thank Rachel Cerny, Our Food Director for working so hard getting all the details ironed out; Our Fearless Leader Angela Hazelett, who will always step in when and where needed to get things done; Jenny McClanahan and Her husband Craig for always stepping up and helping when asked; Gina Trower and her husband Zach who is always willing to lend a hand; & Cindy Mize (taking the pic) who is always working hard to help Rachel do whatever it takes to make things happen. Thank You ALL for the hard work you did today.

For more information on the lunches being provided click on the link below; school website, or Twitter.

post_text:
Congratulations Isaac Black!!

Highland student Isaac Black has been named a finalist for The Semper Fidelis All-American program. The program recognizes high school students who face life's battles with conviction and determination to succeed. Students must meet minimum requirements for nomination:
Junior in high school
3.5 of higher GPA
Be active in community service
Play a competitive team sport
Hold a student or community leadership position
There were 5,603 Nominations, from 989 Schools and 46 States. Isaac is one of 5 finalists from the state of Iowa. For more information on the program, click the link below:

Semper Fidelis All-American Program

Congrats Ike!!!!!!!!!!

Highland Secondary School added 113 new photos — in Riverside, Iowa.
February 28 at 10:26 PM · Riverside, IA ·

We've had a great week at HHS celebrating our FFA/Ag Department & Students. They've done an amazing job all week with daily staff treats, a Staff Appreciation Breakfast, Theme/Dress-up Days and capped off the Week with Ag Olympics. It has been a fun and great week. Well Done Students and Teachers. In Addition, they held a penny drive to raise money for Paws & More by having students vote for the staff members they'd like to kiss animals. They raised over $95.00 that will be donated. Well Done Students!!! #HuskyPride

Another Busy Weekend here at Highland.

Tomorrow our Individual Speech team will be heading to Districts in Wapello to compete to advance to State Competition. They begin tomorrow morning at 8:00 a.m. and we will have students throughout the day competing until 3:00 p.m. Good Luck to the following individuals Hanna Rees, Jacob Allen, Adrie Clendineng, Matt Butler, Caden Jepson, Isaac Black

post_text:
Congratulations to our Highland Huskies Boys Basketball Team on their exciting win last night over North Cedar.

The boys will be playing Thursday night, February 27th @ 7:00 p.m. against Springville at Liberty High in North Liberty.

Below is some information of what you can expect at the game Thursday night. Lets pack the gym and show our Young Men and Coaches some Support.

Liberty High School is located at 1400 S. Dubuque St. North Liberty, IA

Doors for admission will open at 6:00 pm and all tickets are $6.00.

Highland will be visitors, wear their dark colored uniforms, and will sit on the left side of the scorer’s table as you face the floor.

Highland fans will sit on the north side of the gym, behind the scorer’s table. Highland students will be located on the north side behind their team bench.

There will be a concession stand available during the game.

Let's Go Huskies!!!

Another Successful weekend this past weekend for the Finger Tightans. They will be back in Action February 28th & February 29th.

At the Iowa City Super Qualifier on Saturday, the robotics team was on the winning alliance at the end of the competition. They also won the Connect Award, for connecting with the local community, the robotics community, and the engineering community. The team performed well all day, and advanced to the State Championship, which will be held in Cedar Rapids on February 28th and 29th.
Team photo courtesy of Dreamsenses Photography.

post_text: Love the community support! Last Monday we asked if Hills Bank might still have some promotional mice laying around the office that our students could use for ISASP testing in March. (Due to the new testing format our students have to drag a drop some responses and the track pads on their Chromebooks just aren't ideal.) We thought they might be able to scrounge up 20 mice for us...instead we received 320 mice on Friday. Enough to provide for each of our testers at the middle school and high school! Thank you HILLS BANK!

post_text:
Rayne Foley Wins Two Scholastic Writing Awards

8th Grader Rayne Foley has been awarded a Silver Key for her Science Fiction and Fantasy Story, "The Prisoner," and an Honorable Mention for her Flash Fiction, "The Haven" in the 2019 Scholastic Art and Writing Awards. Since 1923, these awards have been recognizing promising writers and artists. Foley joins the list of alumni such as Joyce Carol Oates, Stephen King, Garrison Keillor, Sylvia Plath, and many more. Gold Keys are awarded to the top 5-7% of all entries. Silver Keys are awarded to the top 7-10% of all entries. Honorable Mention is awarded to the top 10-15% of all entries. The district Highland competes in includes the Minneapolis, St. Paul, Kansas City, St. Louis, Chicago, and Detroit. Awards will be held on March 7 at the IMU Ballroom at the U of I. Congratulations, Rayne!!

On Sunday, January 26, 2020; The Highland FFA Chapter held their Greenhand Ceremony. It is amazing how much the FFA Chapter has grown over the last couple of years. A Huge Congratulations to the Advisors, Members, Parents, etc. for helping this program thrive. Great things are happening at Highland and we are just getting started.

Officer Team: President-Bryce Waters; Co-Vice Presidents-Elli Anderson & Jenna Sands; Secretary-Madison Thomann; Treasurer-Jamison Kasperick; Co-Reporters-Brock Schaedler & Taylor Sublette; Sentinel-Thomas Rittenmeyer; Co-Historians-Mackinze Hora & Madeline Peiffer.

Discovery Degrees: Grace Prybil; Kerra Longbine; Payton Brun; Jack Peiffer; Braden Johnston; Aaron Schaedler; Cody Strait; Brandon Holm & Remington Fields.

Greenhand Degrees: Avery Johnston; Jenna Waters; Katelyn Waters; MyLei Smith; Addy Kleopfer; Peyton Yeggy; Lillie Pierce; Brooke Rarick; DJ Jones & Tyler Hoppman.

Chapter Degrees: Mackinze Hora; Carsen Mellinger; Dakota Longbine; Maddie Peiffer; Jalynn Brown & Jamison Kasparek.

Photo Credits: Christina Waters & Cindy Peiffer

Tomorrow, Saturday, January 25, 2020; we have 8 students that will be travelling to Lone Tree to compete in the Large Group Districts competition. They are:

Kadin Jepsen- Group Improv (2)
Jacob Allen- Group Improv (2) (Junior)
Isaac Black- Group Improv (2) (Junior)
Kyle Whestine- Group Improv (2) (Sophomore)
Emma Nicola- Group Improv, Radio News (Sophomore)
Zyppi Willis- Group Improv (Freshman)
Zoey Robidoux- Group Improv (Sophomore)
Matt Butler- Radio News (Senior)
Brendan Schnoebelen- Radio News (Freshman)

Matt will not be traveling with us as he will be at a Robotics competition on the same day. He will be competing in the Radio Newscast in which the three students recorded a short radio skit that will be played at competition. The Improvers will all be competing at scheduled times and will perform a skit up to 5 minutes based on a situation that they choose at competition.

Best of Luck

#HuskyPride

post_text:
Tomorrow, Saturday, January 25, 2020; the Highland robotics team has their league championship in Ottumwa at Indian Hills Community College. They will compete with 22 other teams for a chance to advance to the next round of competition, which is a super qualifier in Iowa City. Advancement at the super qualifier would send them to the state competition. At the league championship they may advance based on the performance of their robot, or based on their interview,and Engineering notebook, where they will highlight their journey this year and all of the community outreach they've done to promote robotics and to learn from the engineering community.

Best Of Luck Team.

#HuskyPride
